  "final_answer": "## Users-Per-Satellite Ratio Analysis (as of March 31, 2026)\n\n### Clarification on Satellite Counts\nThe S-1 filing states ~9,600 is the **combined** total of broadband AND mobile satellites. The filing separately discloses ~9,000 broadband satellites and ~650 V1 Mobile satellites.\n\n### Calculated Ratios\n\n| Network | Satellites | Users/Devices | Users-per-Satellite |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Broadband** | ~9,000 | 10.3M subscribers | **~1,144 users/satellite** |\n| **V1 Mobile** | ~650 | 7.4M monthly unique devices | **~11,385 devices/satellite** |\n\nThe mobile network operates at approximately **~10× the user density** of the broadband network.\n\n### Key Utilization Implications\n\n1. **Different service profiles explain the gap:** V1 Mobile delivers lightweight services (SMS, light data, OTT voice) vs. broadband's high-throughput demands (median 225 Mbps peak-hour speeds).\n\n2. **Broadband has substantial headroom:** >700 Tbps cumulative capacity across the fleet yields ~73 Gbps/satellite and ~68 Mbps theoretical per-subscriber capacity, with concurrent utilization well below saturation.\n\n3. **Mobile is approaching V1 limits:** With ~11,385 devices per satellite and subscriber growth (105% YoY) outpacing mobile satellite deployment (~81% increase), SpaceX is planning V2 Mobile satellites (2027) and a $19.6B EchoStar spectrum acquisition to increase mobile capacity by \"orders of magnitude.\"\n\n4. **Starship is the capacity multiplier:** V3 broadband satellites (1 Tbps each, deploying H2 2026 via Starship at 60 per launch — a 20× improvement over Falcon 9) will dramatically reduce broadband user density and increase per-user bandwidth.",
  "final_error": null,
